The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas reduction (GES) that corresponds almost to one third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún in order to compensate for the absence of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if the incandescent ampoules that monopolies still from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluo-compact ampoules or, better, by electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED") ampoules, the main of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should lead to global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will have to be removed from this budget another 5 Gt to stabilize the 2-centigrade climate by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In the incandescent ampoules, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced from light.
With fluo-compact ampoules, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new DEL ampoules, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluo-compact ampoules last from 6000 to 10,000 hours on average.
New pumps in DEL, such as those launched by Philips manufacturer this week - this company has also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the economy possible with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
All these new ampoules can also work with reeostats, as well as very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have made reservations to the place of fluo-compact ampoules as they contain mercury and have to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluo-compact ampoule, but rather the thermal power plants in coal, which emit a lot of mercury to produce spent electricity in incandescent ampoules.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
